comments.text:
Only Tamers is courageous and gutsy enough to kill off a long time character like that. Hopefully we get to see more of his ghost form when he isn't in hell. 

Once again we see Tamers, being the true artist he is, tap into some very profound themes here. Some hard truths about the human condition that many would prefer not to think about. Blaise Pascal, the great Mathematician and philosopher, spoke often of how we humans have an addiction to distraction: we distract ourselves with meaningless activities in order to avoid thinking about things such as the inevitably of death. Tamers sees this, and forces his viewers to confront these bleak realities such as death, heartbreak, betrayal, adultery, envy, deceit, and cruelty. 

But like Blaise Pascal, there is also hope. Blaise Pascal was a devout Christian and so understood that, when we free ourselves from distraction and consider these questions, if we seek the truth we shall know God. On the same token, Tamers knows that if we consider these questions as he presents them, and we truly and honestly think about them, we will come to know how truly awesome Bartleby and his love for Sonic is. 

Tamers is this generation's great artist, and belongs at the highest level in the pantheon of artistic greats. He understands drama better than Marlowe and even Shakespeare, is a poet to make Homer and Ovid jealous, and William Blake could learn a thing or two about painting from Lord Tamers.

Tamers is a renaissance man; he can do it all. Drawing, voice acting, writing, composing, you name it! His love of Sonic Underground allows him to do great things the rest of us can only dream of. Truly, the cultural, artistic, and intellectual future of the human race will all be downhill after this. Humanity will never again reach such heights as Tamers12345.
